The reason why your columns are generated as `BigInteger` is because they&#39;re of type `NUMERIC(n, 0)`, `NUMBER(n, 0)`, or `DECIMAL(n, 0)` depending on the dialect you&#39;re using, but the key here is that the scale is `0`, and `n` is large enough that it doesn&#39;t fit in a `Long` anymore.

The reason why your `&lt;forcedType/&gt;` configuration hasn&#39;t worked is because the type you&#39;ve listed in `&lt;types/&gt;` is the Java type `BigInteger`, not the `SQLDataType`, [see documentation here][1]. In order to rewrite all zero scale decimals to produce `BigDecimal`, just write this:

```xml
&lt;forcedType&gt;
  &lt;name&gt;NUMERIC&lt;/name&gt;
  &lt;inputTypes&gt;(?i:(NUMERIC|NUMBER|DECIMAL)\(\d+,0\))&lt;/inputTypes&gt;
&lt;/forcedType&gt;
```

You won&#39;t need a custome converter for that


  [1]: https://www.jooq.org/doc/latest/manual/code-generation/codegen-advanced/codegen-config-database/codegen-database-forced-types/

