The words in the initial array can be sorted using comparator for the converted string built from the sorted character array of the given word:
```java
public static String convert(String s) {
    char[] c = s.toLowerCase().toCharArray();
    Arrays.sort(c);
    return new String(c);
}
```
```java
String[] data = {&quot;Banana&quot;, &quot;Isle&quot;, &quot;Best&quot;, &quot;Barb&quot;, &quot;Abracadabra&quot;, &quot;aardvark&quot;, &quot;Barnabie&quot;};
Arrays.sort(data, Comparator.comparing(MyClass::convert));
System.out.println(Arrays.toString(data));
```
Output:
```
[Abracadabra, Banana, aardvark, Barnabie, Barb, Best, Isle]
```

Although this method has some preparation and is relatively long it is does reasonably well on small lists and very well on very large lists.  Its chief advantages are:
- It computes the frequency count on the fly and only once per word.
- the only sorting is done on the word list itself.
- no additional computation is repeated within the comparator.


So  First build a comparator.
- First compare the values in the first location in the array (the `a` count).
- then append each possible location of the next count using `thenComparing`
- finally, reverse the entire comparator to sort in reverse order.
```
Comparator&lt;int[]&gt; comp = Comparator.comparing(a -&gt; a[0]);
for (int i = 1; i &lt; 26; i++) {
	final int g = i;
	comp = comp.thenComparing(a -&gt; a[g]);
}
comp = comp.reversed();
```
Now define a `Function` to get the letter frequency count of each word. This function takes a word and returns an int array of 26 values for the count of letters `a-z` in each word.  The count is case-insensitive.
```
Function&lt;String, int[]&gt; frequency = (word) -&gt; {
	int[] counts = new int[26];
	for (char ch : word.toCharArray()) {
		counts[Character.toLowerCase(ch)
				- &#39;a&#39;]++;
	}
	return counts;
};
```
Now its time to sort.  Putting it all together:
- stream the words
- create an `Entry` for each word where the `key` is the word and `value` is the frequency count computed for that word.
- then sort on the `Entry#value` using the previously built comparator.
- and map to the key, and return in a list.
```	
